                                <date>1958</date>. С. <biblScope unit="page">??–??</biblScope>.</bibl></sourceDesc></fileDesc><xi:include href="../encodingdesc.xml" parse="xml"/></teiHeader><text><body><entry xml:id="entry_æda" xml:lang="os"><form type="lemma"><orth>æda</orth></form><sense><sense><abv:tr xml:lang="ru"><q>тятя</q></abv:tr><abv:tr xml:lang="en"><q>daddy</q></abv:tr></sense><sense><abv:tr xml:lang="ru"><q>дедушка</q></abv:tr><abv:tr xml:lang="en"><q>granddad</q></abv:tr></sense><note type="comment" xml:lang="ru">детское и почтительно-ласковое название для отца, деда:</note><note type="comment" xml:lang="en">childish and respectfull diminutive name for father, grandfather:</note></sense><abv:exampleGrp><abv:example><quote>dy, æda, ūcy læppūjy ærra xonys, fælæ ūmæj zondǵyndær næ bæsty bīræ ne ʽssarʒynæ</quote><abv:tr xml:lang="ru"><q>ты, тятя, зовешь того юношу дурнем, но умнее его ты немного найдешь в нашей округе</q></abv:tr><abv:tr xml:lang="en"><q>you, daddy, call that young man a fool, but you will find few who are smarter than him in our district</q></abv:tr><bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#src_ОТ"/><biblScope>95</biblScope></bibl></abv:example></abv:exampleGrp><etym xml:lang="ru">Ср. <mentioned xml:lang="tr"><lang/> <w>ata</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="alt"><lang/> <w>ada</w> <gloss><q>отец</q></gloss></mentioned>. Широко распространено в кавказских языках: <mentioned xml:lang="kbd"><lang/> <w>hade</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="x-crc"><lang/> <w>atte</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ce" extralang="inh"><lang/> <w>da</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="dar"><lang/> <w>ada</w> <gloss><q>отец</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="dar"><w/> <gloss><q>дед</q></gloss></mentioned> (при <mentioned xml:lang="av"><lang/> <w>ada</w> <gloss><q>бабушка</q></gloss></mentioned>) и др. Как детское слово, оно не связано с какой-либо одной языковой группой, ср. <mentioned xml:lang="grc"><lang/> <w>ἄττα</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="la"><lang/> <w>atta</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="got"><lang/> <w>atta</w></mentioned> atta, <mentioned xml:lang="hit"><lang/> <w>attaš</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ru"><lang/> <w>отец</w></mentioned> (при <mentioned xml:lang="sa"><lang/> <w>attā-</w> <gloss><q>мать</q></gloss></mentioned>); далее <mentioned xml:lang="hu"><lang/> <w>atja</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="kca" dialect="kca"><lang/> <w>ata</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="udm"><lang/> <w>ata, ataj</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="fi"><lang/> <w>ättä</w></mentioned> и др. Симметричный термин для ‘матери’ -— <ref type="xr" target="#entry_æna"/> q. v. См. также <ref type="xr" target="#entry_dada"/>, <ref type="xr" target="#entry_nana"/>.</etym><etym xml:lang="en">Cf. <mentioned xml:lang="tr"><lang/> <w>ata</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="alt"><lang/> <w>ada</w> <gloss><q>отец</q></gloss></mentioned>. Widespread in Caucasian languages: <mentioned xml:lang="kbd"><lang/> <w>hade</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="x-crc"><lang/> <w>atte</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ce" extralang="inh"><lang/> <w>da</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="dar"><lang/> <w>ada</w> <gloss><q>father</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="dar"><w/> <gloss><q>grandfather</q></gloss></mentioned> (but <mentioned xml:lang="av"><lang/> <w>ada</w> <gloss><q>grandmother</q></gloss></mentioned>) etc. As a childish word, it is not associated with any one language group, cf. <mentioned xml:lang="grc"><lang/> <w>ἄττα</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="la"><lang/> <w>atta</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="got"><lang/> <w>atta</w></mentioned> atta, <mentioned xml:lang="hit"><lang/> <w>attaš</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ru"><lang/> <w>отец</w></mentioned> (при <mentioned xml:lang="sa"><lang/> <w>attā-</w> <gloss><q>mother</q></gloss></mentioned>); further, <mentioned xml:lang="hu"><lang/> <w>atja</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="kca" dialect="kca"><lang/> <w>ata</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="udm"><lang/> <w>ata, ataj</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="fi"><lang/> <w>ättä</w></mentioned> etc. Symmetrical term for ‘mother’ is <ref type="xr" target="#entry_æna"/> q. v. See also <ref type="xr" target="#entry_dada"/>, <ref type="xr" target="#entry_nana"/>.</etym></entry></body></text></TEI>